{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618113"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.1,0.02,0.65,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66304"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51753"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5087"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22182"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66304"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman with pulmonary hypertension is prescribed epoprostenol, a synthetic prostacyclin analogue. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes her medication\u0027s primary physiological effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchodilation and mucus secretion","Vasoconstriction and platelet activation","Bronchoconstriction and inflammation","Vasodilation and platelet inhibition","Vasoconstriction and bronchodilation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary physiological effect of prostacyclin involves \u003Cstrong\u003Evasodilation and platelet inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E. It acts through specific prostacyclin receptors coupled to G-proteins, leading to increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) in target cells. This results in smooth muscle relaxation and reduced platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchodilation and mucus secretion\u003C/strong\u003E: while prostacyclin may cause mild bronchodilation, this is not its primary physiological effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction and platelet activation\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the opposite of prostacyclin\u0027s effects and better characterises thromboxane A2 actions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoconstriction and inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E: while some prostaglandins cause bronchoconstriction, this is not a primary effect of prostacyclin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction and bronchodilation\u003C/strong\u003E: this combination is incorrect as prostacyclin is a vasodilator.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProstacyclin\u0027s vasodilatory and anti-platelet effects make it an important mediator in maintaining vascular homeostasis and preventing thrombosis. Synthetic prostacyclin analogues are used therapeutically in conditions like pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prostacyclin (prostaglandin I2) is a potent vasodilator that also inhibits platelet aggregation.","Prostacyclin acts by binding to specific receptors that increase cyclic adenosine monophosphate levels in target cells.","Prostacyclin is synthesised from arachidonic acid via the cyclooxygenase pathway."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51753"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16496"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51753"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:38:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:15:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9187"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66304"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":n